{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584128"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:38:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:38:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14401"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14401"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.37,0,0.53,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7096"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57258"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7096"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42717"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4900"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16932"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17124"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57258"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe internal surface of the heart chambers contains various anatomical features that contribute to their structure and function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following are the muscular striations found in the right atrium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conus arteriosus","Trabeculae carneae","Septomarginal trabecula","Pectinate muscles","Aortic vestibule"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epectinate muscles\u003C/strong\u003E are the correct answer, as they are the muscular striations found in the right atrium of the heart (and also in the left atrium). They are thin, parallel ridges of muscle that help increase the surface area of the atrial wall and assist in the contraction of the atrium during the cardiac cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Econus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E is a conical pouch formed by the upper end of the right ventricle, from which the pulmonary artery arises. It is not found in the right atrium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrabeculae carneae\u003C/strong\u003E are irregular muscular columns that project from the inner surface of the left and right ventricles, but not the atria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptomarginal trabecula\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as the moderator band, is a muscular band in the right ventricle that connects the interventricular septum to the anterior papillary muscle. It is not present in the right atrium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic vestibule\u003C/strong\u003E is the part of the left ventricle just below the aortic valve, forming a smooth-walled channel for blood flow into the aorta. It is not a feature of the right atrium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pectinate muscles are the muscular striations found in the right atrium of the heart.","Pectinate muscles are parallel ridges of cardiac muscle tissue located in the right atrial appendage and on the right atrial wall."],"references":["Tan NY, Yasin OZ, Sugrue A, El Sabbagh A, Foley TA, Asirvatham SJ. Anatomy and Physiologic Roles of the Left Atrial Appendage: Implications for Endocardial and Epicardial Device Closure. Interv Cardiol Clin. 2018 Apr;7(2):185-199. doi: 10.1016/j.iccl.2017.12.001. PMID: 29526287.","Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42717"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14401"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42717"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T18:03:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T18:04:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7096"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57258"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"